# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hetzner-cloud
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] In information technology, a **backup**, or **data backup** is a copy of computer data taken and stored elsewhere so that it may be used to **restore** the original after a data loss event.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The verb form, referring to the process of doing so, is "back up", whereas the noun and adjective form is "backup".
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Backups can be used to recover data after its loss from data deletion or corruption, or to recover data from an earlier time.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Backups provide a simple form of IT disaster recovery; however not all backup systems are able to reconstitute a computer system or other complex configuration such as a computer cluster, active directory server, or database server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A backup system contains at least one copy of all data considered worth saving.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The data storage requirements can be large.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] An information repository model may be used to provide structure to this storage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] There are different types of data storage devices used for copying backups of data that is already in secondary storage onto archive files.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] There are also different ways these devices can be arranged to provide geographic dispersion, data security, and portability.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Data is selected, extracted, and manipulated for storage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The process can include methods for dealing with live data, including open files, as well as compression, encryption, and de-duplication.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Additional techniques apply to enterprise client-server backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Backup schemes may include dry runs that validate the reliability of the data being backed up.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] There are limitations and human factors involved in any backup scheme.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A backup strategy requires an information repository, "a secondary storage space for data" that aggregates backups of data "sources".
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The repository could be as simple as a list of all backup media (DVDs, etc.) and the dates produced, or could include a computerized index, catalog, or relational database.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The backup data needs to be stored, requiring a backup rotation scheme, which is a system of backing up data to computer media that limits the number of backups of different dates retained separately, by appropriate re-use of the data storage media by overwriting of backups no longer needed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The scheme determines how and when each piece of removable storage is used for a backup operation and how long it is retained once it has backup data stored on it.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The 3-2-1 rule can aid in the backup process.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] It states that there should be at least 3 copies of the data, stored on 2 different types of storage media, and one copy should be kept offsite, in a remote location (this can include cloud storage).
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] 2 or more different media should be used to eliminate data loss due to similar reasons (for example, optical discs may tolerate being underwater while LTO tapes may not, and SSDs cannot fail due to head crashes or damaged spindle motors since they do not have any moving parts, unlike hard drives).
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] An offsite copy protects against fire, theft of physical media (such as tapes or discs) and natural disasters like floods and earthquakes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Physically protected hard drives are an alternative to an offsite copy, but they have limitations like only being able to resist fire for a limited period of time, so an offsite copy still remains as the ideal choice.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Because there is no perfect storage, many backup experts recommend maintaining a second copy on a local physical device, even if the data is also backed up offsite.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] An unstructured repository may simply be a stack of tapes, DVD-Rs or external HDDs with minimal information about what was backed up and when.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This method is the easiest to implement, but unlikely to achieve a high level of recoverability as it lacks automation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A repository using this backup method contains complete source data copies taken at one or more specific points in time.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Copying system images, this method is frequently used by computer technicians to record known good configurations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] However, imaging is generally more useful as a way of deploying a standard configuration to many systems rather than as a tool for making ongoing backups of diverse systems.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] An incremental backup stores data changed since a reference point in time.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Duplicate copies of unchanged data are not copied.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Typically a full backup of all files is made once or at infrequent intervals, serving as the reference point for an incremental repository.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Subsequently, a number of incremental backups are made after successive time periods.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Restores begin with the last full backup and then apply the incrementals.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Some backup systems can create a synthetic full backup from a series of incrementals, thus providing the equivalent of frequently doing a full backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] When done to modify a single archive file, this speeds restores of recent versions of files.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Continuous Data Protection (CDP) refers to a backup that instantly saves a copy of every change made to the data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This allows restoration of data to any point in time and is the most comprehensive and advanced data protection.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Near-CDP backup applications—often marketed as "CDP"—automatically take incremental backups at a specific interval, for example every 15 minutes, one hour, or 24 hours.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] They can therefore only allow restores to an interval boundary.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Near-CDP backup applications use journaling and are typically based on periodic "snapshots", read-only copies of the data frozen at a particular point in time.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Near-CDP (except for Apple Time Machine) intent-logs every change on the host system, often by saving byte or block-level differences rather than file-level differences.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This backup method differs from simple disk mirroring in that it enables a roll-back of the log and thus a restoration of old images of data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Near-CDP is more practicable for ordinary personal backup applications, as opposed to *true* CDP, which must be run in conjunction with a virtual machine or equivalent and is therefore generally used in enterprise client-server backups.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Software may create copies of individual files such as written documents, multimedia projects, or user preferences, to prevent failed write events caused by power outages, operating system crashes, or exhausted disk space, from causing data loss.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A common implementation is an appended ".bak" extension to the file name.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A Reverse incremental backup method stores a recent archive file "mirror" of the source data and a series of differences between the "mirror" in its current state and its previous states.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A reverse incremental backup method starts with a non-image full backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] After the full backup is performed, the system periodically synchronizes the full backup with the live copy, while storing the data necessary to reconstruct older versions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This can either be done using hard links—as Apple Time Machine does, or using binary diffs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A differential backup saves only the data that has changed since the last full backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This means a maximum of two backups from the repository are used to restore the data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] However, as time from the last full backup (and thus the accumulated changes in data) increases, so does the time to perform the differential backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Restoring an entire system requires starting from the most recent full backup and then applying just the last differential backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Changes in files may be detected through a more recent date/time of last modification file attribute, and/or changes in file size.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Other variations of incremental backup include multi-level incrementals and block-level incrementals that compare parts of files instead of just entire files.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Regardless of the repository model that is used, the data has to be copied onto an archive file data storage medium.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The medium used is also referred to as the type of backup destination.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Magnetic tape was for a long time the most commonly used medium for bulk data storage, backup, archiving, and interchange.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] It was previously a less expensive option, but this is no longer the case for smaller amounts of data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Tape is a sequential access medium, so the rate of continuously writing or reading data can be very fast.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] While tape media itself has a low cost per space, tape drives are typically dozens of times as expensive as hard disk drives and optical drives.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Tape media are generally rotated on a schedule so at least one set is off-site in case something should happen to the building where the primary copy of the data lives.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Many tape formats have been proprietary or specific to certain markets like mainframes or a particular brand of personal computer.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] By 2014 LTO had become the primary tape technology.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The other remaining viable "super" format is the IBM 3592 (also referred to as the TS11xx series).
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The Oracle StorageTek T10000 was discontinued in 2016.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The use of hard disk storage has increased over time as it has become progressively cheaper.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Hard disks are usually easy to use, widely available, and can be accessed quickly.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] However, hard disk backups are close-tolerance mechanical devices and may be more easily damaged than tapes, especially while being transported.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Some manufacturers also offer 'ruggedized' portable hard drives, which include a shock-absorbing case around the hard disk, and claim a range of higher drop specifications.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Over a period of years the stability of hard disk backups is shorter than that of tape backups.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] External hard disks can be connected via local interfaces like SCSI, USB, FireWire, or eSATA, or via longer-distance technologies like Ethernet, iSCSI, or Fibre Channel.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Some disk-based backup systems, via Virtual Tape Libraries or otherwise, support data deduplication, which can reduce the amount of disk storage capacity consumed by daily and weekly backup data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Optical storage uses lasers to store and retrieve data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Recordable CDs, DVDs, and Blu-ray Discs are commonly used with personal computers and are generally cheap.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The capacities and speeds of these discs have typically been lower than hard disks or tapes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Advances in optical media may shrink that gap in the future.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Potential future data losses caused by gradual media degradation can be predicted by measuring the rate of correctable minor data errors, of which consecutively too many increase the risk of uncorrectable sectors.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Support for error scanning varies among optical drive vendors.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Many optical disc formats are WORM type, which makes them useful for archival purposes since the data cannot be changed in any way, including by user error and by malware such as ransomware.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Moreover, optical discs are not vulnerable to head crashes, magnetism, imminent water ingress or power surges; and, a fault of the drive typically just halts the spinning.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Optical media is modular; the storage controller is not tied to media itself like with hard drives or flash storage (→flash memory controller), allowing it to be removed and accessed through a different drive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] However, recordable media may degrade earlier under long-term exposure to light.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Some optical storage systems allow for cataloged data backups without human contact with the discs, allowing for longer data integrity.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A French study in 2008 indicated that the lifespan of typically-sold CD-Rs was 2–10 years, but one manufacturer later estimated the longevity of its CD-Rs with a gold-sputtered layer to be as high as 100 years.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Sony's proprietary Optical Disc Archive can in 2016 reach a read rate of 250 MB/s.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Solid-state drives (SSDs) use integrated circuit assemblies to store data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Flash memory, thumb drives, USB flash drives, CompactFlash, SmartMedia, Memory Sticks, and Secure Digital card devices are relatively expensive for their low capacity, but convenient for backing up relatively low data volumes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A solid-state drive does not contain any movable parts, making it less susceptible to physical damage, and can have huge throughput of around 500 Mbit/s up to 6 Gbit/s.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Available SSDs have become more capacious and cheaper.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Flash memory backups are stable for fewer years than hard disk backups.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Remote backup services or cloud backups involve service providers storing data offsite.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This has been used to protect against events such as fires, floods, or earthquakes which could destroy locally stored backups.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Cloud-based backup (through services like or similar to Google Drive, and Microsoft OneDrive) provides a layer of data protection.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] However, the users must trust the provider to maintain the privacy and integrity of their data, with confidentiality enhanced by the use of encryption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Because speed and availability are limited by a user's online connection, users with large amounts of data may need to use seed loading and bulk restore.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Various methods can be used to manage backup media, striking a balance between accessibility, security and cost.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] These media management methods are not mutually exclusive and are frequently combined to meet the user's needs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Using on-line disks for staging data before it is sent to a near-line tape library is a common example.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Online backup storage is typically the most accessible type of data storage, and can begin a restore in milliseconds.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] An internal hard disk or a disk array (maybe connected to SAN) is an example of an online backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This type of storage is convenient and speedy, but is vulnerable to being deleted or overwritten, either by accident, by malevolent action, or in the wake of a data-deleting virus payload.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Nearline storage is typically less accessible and less expensive than online storage, but still useful for backup data storage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A mechanical device is usually used to move media units from storage into a drive where the data can be read or written.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Generally it has safety properties similar to on-line storage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] An example is a tape library with restore times ranging from seconds to a few minutes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Off-line storage requires some direct action to provide access to the storage media: for example, inserting a tape into a tape drive or plugging in a cable.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Because the data is not accessible via any computer except during limited periods in which they are written or read back, they are largely immune to on-line backup failure modes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Access time varies depending on whether the media are on-site or off-site.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Backup media may be sent to an off-site vault to protect against a disaster or other site-specific problem.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The vault can be as simple as a system administrator's home office or as sophisticated as a disaster-hardened, temperature-controlled, high-security bunker with facilities for backup media storage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A data replica can be off-site but also on-line (e.g., an off-site RAID mirror).
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A backup site or disaster recovery center is used to store data that can enable computer systems and networks to be restored and properly configured in the event of a disaster.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Some organisations have their own data recovery centres, while others contract this out to a third-party.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Due to high costs, backing up is rarely considered the preferred method of moving data to a DR site.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A more typical way would be remote disk mirroring, which keeps the DR data as up to date as possible.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A backup operation starts with selecting and extracting coherent units of data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Most data on modern computer systems is stored in discrete units, known as files.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] These files are organized into filesystems.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Deciding what to back up at any given time involves tradeoffs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] By backing up too much redundant data, the information repository will fill up too quickly.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Backing up an insufficient amount of data can eventually lead to the loss of critical information.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Files that are actively being updated present a challenge to back up.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] One way to back up live data is to temporarily quiesce them (e.g., close all files), take a "snapshot", and then resume live operations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] At this point the snapshot can be backed up through normal methods.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] A snapshot is an instantaneous function of some filesystems that presents a copy of the filesystem as if it were frozen at a specific point in time, often by a copy-on-write mechanism.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Snapshotting a file while it is being changed results in a corrupted file that is unusable.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This is also the case across interrelated files, as may be found in a conventional database or in applications such as Microsoft Exchange Server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The term fuzzy backup can be used to describe a backup of live data that looks like it ran correctly, but does not represent the state of the data at a single point in time.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Not all information stored on the computer is stored in files.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Accurately recovering a complete system from scratch requires keeping track of this non-file data too.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] It is frequently useful or required to manipulate the data being backed up to optimize the backup process.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] These manipulations can improve backup speed, restore speed, data security, media usage and/or reduced bandwidth requirements.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Out-of-date data can be automatically deleted, but for personal backup applications—as opposed to enterprise client-server backup applications where automated data "grooming" can be customized—the deletion can at most be globally delayed or be disabled.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Various schemes can be employed to shrink the size of the source data to be stored so that it uses less storage space.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Compression is frequently a built-in feature of tape drive hardware.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Redundancy due to backing up similarly configured workstations can be reduced, thus storing just one copy.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This technique can be applied at the file or raw block level.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This potentially large reduction is called deduplication.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] It can occur on a server before any data moves to backup media, sometimes referred to as source/client side deduplication.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This approach also reduces bandwidth required to send backup data to its target media.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The process can also occur at the target storage device, sometimes referred to as inline or back-end deduplication.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Sometimes backups are duplicated to a second set of storage media.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This can be done to rearrange the archive files to optimize restore speed, or to have a second copy at a different location or on a different storage medium—as in the disk-to-disk-to-tape capability of Enterprise client-server backup.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] High-capacity removable storage media such as backup tapes present a data security risk if they are lost or stolen.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Encrypting the data on these media can mitigate this problem, however encryption is a CPU intensive process that can slow down backup speeds, and the security of the encrypted backups is only as effective as the security of the key management policy.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] When there are many more computers to be backed up than there are destination storage devices, the ability to use a single storage device with several simultaneous backups can be useful.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] However cramming the scheduled backup window via "multiplexed backup" is only used for tape destinations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] The process of rearranging the sets of backups in an archive file is known as refactoring.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] For example, if a backup system uses a single tape each day to store the incremental backups for all the protected computers, restoring one of the computers could require many tapes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Refactoring could be used to consolidate all the backups for a single computer onto a single tape, creating a "synthetic full backup".
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This is especially useful for backup systems that do incrementals forever style backups.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] Sometimes backups are copied to a staging disk before being copied to tape.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] This process is sometimes referred to as D2D2T, an acronym for Disk-to-disk-to-tape.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] It can be useful if there is a problem matching the speed of the final destination device with the source device, as is frequently faced in network-based backup systems.
[src:hetzner-cloud/backup] It can also serve as a centralized location for applying other data manipulation techniques.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2011, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) identified five "essential characteristics" for cloud systems.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] By 2023, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO) had expanded and refined the list.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The history of cloud computing extends to the 1960s, with the initial concepts of time-sharing becoming popularized via remote job entry (RJE).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The "data center" model, where users submitted jobs to operators to run on mainframes, was predominantly used during this era.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This period saw broad experimentation with making large-scale computing power more accessible through time-sharing, while optimizing infrastructure, platforms, and applications to improve efficiency for end users.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The "cloud" metaphor for virtualized services dates to 1994, when it was used by General Magic for the universe of "places" that mobile agents in the Telescript environment could "go".
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor is credited to David Hoffman, a General Magic communications specialist, based on its long-standing use in networking and telecom.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The expression *cloud computing* became more widely known in 1996 when Compaq Computer Corporation drew up a business plan for future computing and the Internet.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The company's ambition was to supercharge sales with "cloud computing-enabled applications".
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The business plan foresaw that online consumer file storage would likely be commercially successful.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, Compaq decided to sell server hardware to internet service providers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In the 2000s, the application of cloud computing began to take shape with the establishment of Amazon Web Services (AWS) in 2002, which allowed developers to build applications independently.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2006 Amazon Simple Storage Service, known as Amazon S3, and the Amazon Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) were released.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2008 NASA's development of the first open-source software for deploying private and hybrid clouds.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The following decade saw the launch of various cloud services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2010, Microsoft launched Microsoft Azure, and Rackspace Hosting and NASA initiated an open-source cloud-software project, OpenStack.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] IBM introduced the IBM SmartCloud framework in 2011, and Oracle announced the Oracle Cloud in 2012.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In December 2019, Amazon launched AWS Outposts, a service that extends AWS infrastructure, services, APIs, and tools to customer data centers, co-location spaces, or on-premises facilities.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing can shorten time to market by offering pre-configured tools, scalable resources, and managed services, allowing users to focus on core business value rather than maintaining infrastructure.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms can enable organizations and individuals to reduce upfront capital expenditures on physical infrastructure by shifting to an operational expenditure model, where costs scale with usage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud platforms also offer managed services and tools, such as artificial intelligence, data analytics, and machine learning, which might otherwise require significant in-house expertise and infrastructure investment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] While cloud computing can offer cost advantages through effective resource optimization, organizations often face challenges such as unused resources, inefficient configurations, and hidden costs without proper oversight and governance.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud platforms provide cost management tools, such as AWS Cost Explorer and Azure Cost Management, and frameworks like FinOps have emerged to standardize financial operations in the cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing also facilitates collaboration, remote work, and global service delivery by enabling secure access to data and applications from any location with an internet connection.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers offer various redundancy options for core services, such as managed storage and managed databases, though redundancy configurations often vary by service tier.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Advanced redundancy strategies, such as cross-region replication or failover systems, typically require explicit configuration and may incur additional costs or licensing fees.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud environments operate under a shared responsibility model, where providers are typically responsible for infrastructure security, physical hardware, and software updates, while customers are accountable for data encryption, identity and access management (IAM), and application-level security.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The decision to adopt cloud computing or maintain on-premises infrastructure depends on factors such as scalability, cost structure, latency requirements, regulatory constraints, and infrastructure customization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Organizations with variable or unpredictable workloads, limited capital for upfront investments, or a focus on rapid scalability benefit from cloud adoption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Startups, SaaS companies, and e-commerce platforms often prefer the pay-as-you-go operational expenditure (OpEx) model of cloud infrastructure.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies prioritizing global accessibility, remote workforce enablement, disaster recovery, and leveraging advanced services such as AI/ML and analytics are well-suited for the cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, some cloud providers have started offering specialized services for high-performance computing and low-latency applications, addressing some use cases previously exclusive to on-premises setups.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] On the other hand, organizations with strict regulatory requirements, highly predictable workloads, or reliance on deeply integrated legacy systems may find cloud infrastructure less suitable.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Businesses in industries like defense, government, or those handling highly sensitive data often favor on-premises setups for greater control and data sovereignty.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, companies with ultra-low latency requirements, such as high-frequency trading (HFT) firms, rely on custom hardware (e.g., FPGAs) and physical proximity to exchanges, which most cloud providers cannot fully replicate despite recent advancements.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Similarly, tech giants like Google, Meta, and Amazon build their own data centers due to economies of scale, predictable workloads, and the ability to customize hardware and network infrastructure for optimal efficiency.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] However, these companies also use cloud services selectively for certain workloads and applications where it aligns with their operational needs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In practice, many organizations are increasingly adopting hybrid cloud architectures, combining on-premises infrastructure with cloud services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This approach allows businesses to balance scalability, cost-effectiveness, and control, offering the benefits of both deployment models while mitigating their respective limitations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the primary challenges of cloud computing, compared with traditional on-premises systems, is maintaining data security and privacy.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users entrust their sensitive data to third-party providers, who may not have adequate measures to protect it from unauthorized access, breaches, or leaks.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users also face compliance risks if they have to adhere to certain regulations or standards regarding data protection, such as GDPR or HIPAA.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Another challenge of cloud computing is reduced visibility and control.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users may not have full insight into how their cloud resources are managed, configured, or optimized by their providers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] They may also have limited ability to customize or modify their cloud services according to their specific needs or preferences.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Complete understanding of all technology may be impossible, especially given the scale, complexity, and deliberate opacity of contemporary systems; however, there is a need for understanding complex technologies and their interconnections to have power and agency within them.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The metaphor of the cloud can be seen as problematic as cloud computing retains the aura of something noumenal and numinous; it is something experienced without precisely understanding what it is or how it works.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, cloud migration is a significant challenge.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This process involves transferring data, applications, or workloads from one cloud environment to another, or from on-premises infrastructure to the cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud migration can be complicated, time-consuming, and expensive, particularly when there are compatibility issues between different cloud platforms or architectures.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] If not carefully planned and executed, cloud migration can lead to downtime, reduced performance, or even data loss.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Applications hosted in the cloud are susceptible to the fallacies of distributed computing, a series of misconceptions that can lead to significant issues in software development and deployment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In a report by Gartner, a survey of 200 IT leaders revealed that 69% experienced budget overruns in their organizations' cloud expenditures during 2023.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Conversely, 31% of IT leaders whose organizations stayed within budget attributed their success to accurate forecasting and budgeting, proactive monitoring of spending, and effective optimization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The 2024 Flexera State of Cloud Report identifies the top cloud challenges as managing cloud spend, followed by security concerns and lack of expertise.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Public cloud expenditures exceeded budgeted amounts by an average of 15%.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The report also reveals that cost savings is the top cloud initiative for 60% of respondents.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Furthermore, 65% measure cloud progress through cost savings, while 42% prioritize shorter time-to-market, indicating that cloud's promise of accelerated deployment is often overshadowed by cost concerns.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, cloud providers' Service Level Agreements (SLAs) do not encompass all forms of service interruptions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Exclusions typically include planned maintenance, downtime resulting from external factors such as network issues, human errors, like misconfigurations, natural disasters, force majeure events, or security breaches.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Typically, customers bear the responsibility of monitoring SLA compliance and must file claims for any unmet SLAs within a designated timeframe.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Customers should be aware of how deviations from SLAs are calculated, as these parameters may vary by service.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] These requirements can place a considerable burden on customers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, SLA percentages and conditions can differ across various services within the same provider, with some services lacking any SLA altogether.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In cases of service interruptions due to hardware failures in the cloud provider, the company typically does not offer monetary compensation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Instead, eligible users may receive credits as outlined in the corresponding SLA.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing abstractions aim to simplify resource management, but leaky abstractions can expose underlying complexities.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] These variations in abstraction quality depend on the cloud vendor, service and architecture.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Mitigating leaky abstractions requires users to understand the implementation details and limitations of the cloud services they utilize.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Service lock-in within the same vendor occurs when a customer becomes dependent on specific services within a cloud vendor, making it challenging to switch to alternative services within the same vendor when their needs change.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing poses privacy concerns because the service provider can access the data that is in the cloud at any time.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] It could accidentally or deliberately alter or delete information.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Many cloud providers can share information with third parties if necessary for purposes of law and order without a warrant.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] That is permitted in their privacy policies, which users must agree to before they start using cloud services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Solutions to privacy include policy and legislation as well as end-users' choices for how data is stored.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Users can encrypt data that is processed or stored within the cloud to prevent unauthorized access.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Identity management systems can also provide practical solutions to privacy concerns in cloud computing.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] These systems distinguish between authorized and unauthorized users and determine the amount of data that is accessible to each entity.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The systems work by creating and describing identities, recording activities, and getting rid of unused identities.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] According to the Cloud Security Alliance, the top three threats in the cloud are *Insecure Interfaces and APIs*, *Data Loss & Leakage*, and *Hardware Failure*—which accounted for 29%, 25% and 10% of all cloud security outages respectively.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Together, these form shared technology vulnerabilities.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In a cloud provider platform being shared by different users, there may be a possibility that information belonging to different customers resides on the same data server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Additionally, Eugene Schultz, chief technology officer at Emagined Security, said that hackers are spending substantial time and effort looking for ways to penetrate the cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] "There are some real Achilles' heels in the cloud infrastructure that are making big holes for the bad guys to get into".
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Because data from hundreds or thousands of companies can be stored on large cloud servers, hackers can theoretically gain control of huge stores of information through a single attack—a process he called "hyperjacking".
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Some examples of this include the Dropbox security breach, and iCloud 2014 leak.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Dropbox had been breached in October 2014, having over seven million of its users passwords stolen by hackers in an effort to get monetary value from it by Bitcoins (BTC).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] By having these passwords, they are able to read private data as well as have this data be indexed by search engines (making the information public).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the problem of legal ownership of the data (If a user stores some data in the cloud, can the cloud provider profit from it?).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Many Terms of Service agreements are silent on the question of ownership.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Physical control of the computer equipment (private cloud) is more secure than having the equipment off-site and under someone else's control (public cloud).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This delivers great incentive to public cloud computing service providers to prioritize building and maintaining strong management of secure services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Some small businesses that do not have expertise in IT security could find that it is more secure for them to use a public cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] There is the risk that end users do not understand the issues involved when signing on to a cloud service (persons sometimes do not read the many pages of the terms of service agreement, and just click "Accept" without reading).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This is important now that cloud computing is common and required for some services to work, for example for an intelligent personal assistant (Apple's Siri or Google Assistant).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Fundamentally, private cloud is seen as more secure with higher levels of control for the owner, however public cloud is seen to be more flexible and requires less time and money investment from the user.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The attacks that can be made on cloud computing systems include man-in-the middle attacks, phishing attacks, authentication attacks, and malware attacks.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] One of the largest threats is considered to be malware attacks, such as Trojan horses.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Recent research conducted in 2022 has revealed that the Trojan horse injection method is a serious problem with harmful impacts on cloud computing systems.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The CLOUD Act allows United States authorities to request data from cloud providers, and courts can impose nondisclosure requirements preventing providers from notifying affected users.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This framework is in legal tension with Article 48 of the European General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which restricts the transfer of personal data in response to foreign court or administrative orders unless based on an international agreement.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, cloud service providers operating in both Europe and the U.S. may face competing legal obligations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Donohue writing for the *Harvard Journal of Law and Public Policy*, cloud service providers also fall within the broader category of service providers subject to Section 702 of the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act (FISA), which has had documented effects on cloud providers and their customers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The National Institute of Standards and Technology recognized three cloud service models in 2011: Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) later identified additional models in 2023, including "Network as a Service", "Communications as a Service", "Compute as a Service", and "Data Storage as a Service".
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Infrastructure as a service (IaaS) refers to online services that provide high-level APIs used to abstract various low-level details of underlying network infrastructure like physical computing resources, location, data partitioning, scaling, security, backup, etc.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] A hypervisor runs the virtual machines as guests.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Pools of hypervisors within the cloud operational system can support large numbers of virtual machines and the ability to scale services up and down according to customers' varying requirements.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux containers run in isolated partitions of a single Linux kernel running directly on the physical hardware.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Linux cgroups and namespaces are the underlying Linux kernel technologies used to isolate, secure and manage the containers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The use of containers offers higher performance than virtualization because there is no hypervisor overhead.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS clouds often offer additional resources such as a virtual-machine disk-image library, raw block storage, file or object storage, firewalls, load balancers, IP addresses, virtual local area networks (VLANs), and software bundles.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The NIST's definition of cloud computing describes IaaS as "where the consumer is able to deploy and run arbitrary software, which can include operating systems and applications.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] IaaS-cloud providers supply these resources on-demand from their large pools of equipment installed in data centers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] For wide-area connectivity, customers can use either the Internet or carrier clouds (dedicated virtual private networks).
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] To deploy their applications, cloud users install operating-system images and their application software on the cloud infrastructure.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In this model, the cloud user patches and maintains the operating systems and the application software.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers typically bill IaaS services on a utility computing basis: cost reflects the number of resources allocated and consumed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] PaaS vendors offer a development environment to application developers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The provider typically develops toolkit and standards for development and channels for distribution and payment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In the PaaS models, cloud providers deliver a computing platform, typically including an operating system, programming-language execution environment, database, and the web server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Application developers develop and run their software on a cloud platform instead of directly buying and managing the underlying hardware and software layers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] With some PaaS, the underlying computer and storage resources scale automatically to match application demand so that the cloud user does not have to allocate resources manually.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Some integration and data management providers also use specialized applications of PaaS as delivery models for data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples include **iPaaS (Integration Platform as a Service)** and **dPaaS (Data Platform as a Service)**. iPaaS enables customers to develop, execute and govern integration flows.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the iPaaS integration model, customers drive the development and deployment of integrations without installing or managing any hardware or middleware. dPaaS delivers integration—and data-management—products as a fully managed service.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Under the dPaaS model, the PaaS provider, not the customer, manages the development and execution of programs by building data applications for the customer. dPaaS users access data through data-visualization tools.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In the software as a service (SaaS) model, users gain access to application software and databases.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud providers manage the infrastructure and platforms that run the applications.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS is sometimes referred to as "on-demand software" and is usually priced on a pay-per-use basis or using a subscription fee.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In the SaaS model, cloud providers install and operate application software in the cloud and cloud users access the software from cloud clients.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud users do not manage the cloud infrastructure and platform where the application runs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This eliminates the need to install and run the application on the cloud user's own computers, which simplifies maintenance and support.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud applications differ from other applications in their scalability—which can be achieved by cloning tasks onto multiple virtual machines at run-time to meet changing work demand.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Load balancers distribute the work over the set of virtual machines.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This process is transparent to the cloud user, who sees only a single access-point.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] To accommodate a large number of cloud users, cloud applications can be *multitenant*, meaning that any machine may serve more than one cloud-user organization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The pricing model for SaaS applications is typically a monthly or yearly flat fee per user, so prices become scalable and adjustable if users are added or removed at any point.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Proponents claim that SaaS gives a business the potential to reduce IT operational costs by outsourcing hardware and software maintenance and support to the cloud provider.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This enables the business to reallocate IT operations costs away from hardware/software spending and from personnel expenses, towards meeting other goals.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In addition, with applications hosted centrally, updates can be released without the need for users to install new software.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] One drawback of SaaS comes with storing the users' data on the cloud provider's server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, there could be unauthorized access to the data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Examples of applications offered as SaaS are games and productivity software like Google Docs and Office Online.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] SaaS applications may be integrated with cloud storage or File hosting services, which is the case with Google Docs being integrated with Google Drive, and Office Online being integrated with OneDrive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Serverless computing allows customers to use various cloud capabilities without the need to provision, deploy, or manage hardware or software resources, apart from providing their application code or data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] ISO/IEC 22123-2:2023 classifies serverless alongside Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS), Platform as a Service (PaaS), and Software as a Service (SaaS) under the broader category of cloud service categories.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Notably, while ISO refers to these classifications as cloud service categories, the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) refers to them as service models.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] "A cloud deployment model represents the way in which cloud computing can be organized based on the control and sharing of physical or virtual resources." Cloud deployment models define the fundamental patterns of interaction between cloud customers and cloud providers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] They do not detail implementation specifics or the configuration of resources.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Private cloud is cloud infrastructure operated solely for a single organization, whether managed internally or by a third party, and hosted either internally or externally.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Undertaking a private cloud project requires significant engagement to virtualize the business environment, and requires the organization to reevaluate decisions about existing resources.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] It can improve business, but every step in the project raises security issues that must be addressed to prevent serious vulnerabilities.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Self-run data centers are generally capital intensive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] They have a significant physical footprint, requiring allocations of space, hardware, and environmental controls.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] These assets have to be refreshed periodically, resulting in additional capital expenditures.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] They have attracted criticism because users "still have to buy, build, and manage them" and thus do not benefit from less hands-on management, essentially "[lacking] the economic model that makes cloud computing such an intriguing concept".
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud services are considered "public" when they are delivered over the public Internet, and they may be offered as a paid subscription, or free of charge.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Architecturally, there are few differences between public- and private-cloud services, but security concerns increase substantially when services (applications, storage, and other resources) are shared by multiple customers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Most public-cloud providers offer direct-connection services that allow customers to securely link their legacy data centers to their cloud-resident applications.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Several factors like the functionality of the solutions, cost, integrational and organizational aspects as well as safety & security are influencing the decision of enterprises and organizations to choose a public cloud or on-premises solution.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Varied use cases for hybrid cloud composition exist.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] For example, an organization may store sensitive client data in house on a private cloud application, but interconnect that application to a business intelligence application provided on a public cloud as a software service.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This example of hybrid cloud extends the capabilities of the enterprise to deliver a specific business service through the addition of externally available public cloud services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Hybrid cloud adoption depends on a number of factors such as data security and compliance requirements, level of control needed over data, and the applications an organization uses.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Another example of hybrid cloud is one where IT organizations use public cloud computing resources to meet temporary capacity needs that can not be met by the private cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] This capability enables hybrid clouds to employ cloud bursting for scaling across clouds.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting is an application deployment model in which an application runs in a private cloud or data center and "bursts" to a public cloud when the demand for computing capacity increases.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] A primary advantage of cloud bursting and a hybrid cloud model is that an organization pays for extra compute resources only when they are needed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud bursting enables data centers to create an in-house IT infrastructure that supports average workloads, and use cloud resources from public or private clouds, during spikes in processing demands.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] As a result, only a portion of the potential cost savings of cloud computing is achieved.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] According to ISO/IEC 22123-1: "multi-cloud is a cloud deployment model in which a customer uses public cloud services provided by two or more cloud service providers".
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Poly cloud refers to the use of multiple public clouds for the purpose of leveraging specific services that each provider offers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] It differs from Multi cloud in that it is not designed to increase flexibility or mitigate against failures but is rather used to allow an organization to achieve more than could be done with a single provider.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] According to International Data Corporation (IDC), global spending on cloud computing services has reached $706 billion and is expected to reach $1.3 trillion by 2025.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Gartner estimated that global public cloud services end-user spending would reach $600 billion by 2023.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] According to a McKinsey & Company report, cloud cost-optimization levers and value-oriented business use cases foresee more than $1 trillion in run-rate EBITDA across Fortune 500 companies as up for grabs in 2030.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In 2022, more than $1.3 trillion in enterprise IT spending was at stake from the shift to the cloud, growing to almost $1.8 trillion in 2025, according to Gartner.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The *Communication* set out a series of "digital agenda actions" which the Commission proposed to undertake in order to support the development of a fair and effective market for cloud computing services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] As of 2025, the three largest cloud computing providers by market share, commonly referred to as hyperscalers, are Amazon Web Services (AWS), Microsoft Azure, and Google Cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] These companies dominate the global cloud market due to their extensive infrastructure, broad service offerings, and scalability.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] In recent years, organizations have increasingly adopted alternative cloud providers, which offer specialized services that distinguish them from hyperscalers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Alternative cloud providers are often part of multi-cloud strategies, where organizations use multiple cloud services—both from hyperscalers and specialized providers—to optimize performance, compliance, and cost efficiency.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] However, they do not necessarily serve as direct replacements for hyperscalers, as their offerings are typically more specialized.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The goal of cloud computing is to allow users to take benefit from all of these technologies, without the need for deep knowledge about or expertise with each one of them.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The cloud aims to cut costs and helps the users focus on their core business instead of being impeded by IT obstacles.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] The main enabling technology for cloud computing is virtualization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization software separates a physical computing device into one or more "virtual" devices, each of which can be easily used and managed to perform computing tasks.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] With operating system-level virtualization essentially creating a scalable system of multiple independent computing devices, idle computing resources can be allocated and used more efficiently.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Virtualization provides the agility required to speed up IT operations and reduces cost by increasing infrastructure utilization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Autonomic computing automates the process through which the user can provision resources on-demand.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] By minimizing user involvement, automation speeds up the process, reduces labor costs and reduces the possibility of human errors.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing uses concepts from utility computing to provide metrics for the services used.
[src:hetzner-cloud/cloud-computing] Cloud computing attempts to address QoS (quality of service) and reliability problems of other grid computing models.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Green computing is important for all classes of systems, ranging from handheld systems to large-scale data centers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] According to the International Energy Agency, data centres accounted for about 1.5% of global electricity consumption in 2024 (~415 TWh), and under its central scenario, demand could roughly double to ~945 TWh by 2030, with AI workloads a major driver of growth.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Sustainable development is a concept that redefines the notion of the general interest by integrating environmental, social, and economic considerations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Many corporate IT departments have green computing initiatives to reduce the environmental effect of their IT operations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Yet it is also clear that the environmental footprint of the sector is significant, estimated at 5-9% of the world's total electricity use and more than 2% of all emissions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Data centers and telecommunications networks will need to become more energy efficient, reuse waste energy, use more renewable energy sources, and use less water for cooling to stay competitive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In the European Union, policy efforts and industry initiatives aim for climate-neutral data centers by 2030.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The carbon emissions associated with manufacturing devices and network infrastructures is also a key factor.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Green computing can involve complex trade-offs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] It can be useful to distinguish between IT for environmental sustainability and the environmental sustainability of IT.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Although green IT focuses on the environmental sustainability of IT, in practice these two aspects are often interconnected.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] For example, launching an online shopping platform may increase the carbon footprint of a company's own IT operations, while at the same time helping customers to purchase products remotely, without requiring them to drive, in turn reducing greenhouse gas emission related to travel.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The company might be able to take credit for these decarbonisation benefits under its Scope 3 emissions reporting, which includes emissions from across the entire value chain.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Environmental Protection Agency launched Energy Star, a voluntary labeling program that is designed to promote and recognize the energy efficiency in monitors, climate control equipment, and other technologies.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This resulted in the widespread adoption of sleep mode among consumer electronics.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In 2009 the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) published a survey of over 90 government and industry initiatives on "Green ICTs" (Information and Communication Technologies), the environment and climate change.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The report concluded that initiatives tended to concentrate on the greening ICTs themselves, rather than on their actual implementation to reduce global warming and environmental degradation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In general, only 20% of initiatives had measurable targets, with government programs tending to include targets more frequently than business associations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Many governmental agencies have continued to implement standards and regulations that encourage green computing.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The Energy Star program was revised in October 2006 to include stricter efficiency requirements for computer equipment, along with a tiered ranking system for approved products.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] By 2008, 26 US states established statewide recycling programs for obsolete computers and consumer electronics equipment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The statutes either impose an "advance recovery fee" for each unit sold at retail or require the manufacturers to reclaim the equipment at disposal.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In 2010, the American Recovery and Reinvestment Act (ARRA) was signed into legislation by President Obama.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The bill allocated over $90 billion to be invested in green initiatives (renewable energy, smart grids, energy efficiency, etc.) In January 2010, the U.S.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Energy Department granted $47 million of the ARRA money towards projects to improve the energy efficiency of data centers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The projects provided research to optimize data center hardware and software, improve power supply chain, and data center cooling technologies.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Green digital governance refers to the use of information and communication technology (ICT) to support environmentally sustainable policies and practices.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] It describes a strategy with which an organisation strives to align its information and communications technology with sustainability goals.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This can include using digital tools and platforms to monitor and regulate environmental impact, as well as promoting the development and use of clean and renewable energy sources in the technology sector.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The goal of green digital governance is to reduce the carbon footprint of the digital economy and to support the transition to a more sustainable and resilient society.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Both the green and the digital transitions are on the agenda for most European countries, as well as the EU as a whole.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Documents and goals such as the European Green Deal and the Sustainable Development Goals, fit for 55, Digital Europe and others have begun the transitions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] These two transitions often contradict each other, as digital technologies have substantial environmental footprints that go against the targets of the green transition.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The green transition may accelerate innovation and adoption of digital solutions offering the ICT sector new opportunities for becoming more competitive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The synergy created as a result of the green transition and digitalisation brings social, economic and environmental benefits, which is a goal of environmentally friendly digital governments and the creation of green ICT solutions in general.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The digital component is expected to also be used to reach the ambitions of the European Green Deal and Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] As powerful enablers for the sustainability transition, digital solutions can advance the circular economy, support the decarbonisation of all sectors and reduce the environmental and social footprint of products placed on the EU market.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] For example, key sectors such as precision agriculture, transport and energy can benefit from digital solutions in pursuing the sustainability objectives of the European Green Deal.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] E-government services can provide solutions to the environmental problem.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The possibility for a citizen to fully request and get a service online would render, in addition to cost savings for the public authorities and increased citizen satisfaction, reductions of carbon emissions and paper consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Modern IT systems rely on a complicated mix of people, networks, and hardware; as such, a green computing initiative ideally covers these areas.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] A solution may also need to address end user satisfaction, management restructuring, regulatory compliance, and return on investment (ROI).
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Gartner maintains that the PC manufacturing process accounts for 70% of the natural resources used in the life cycle of a PC.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In 2011, Fujitsu released a life-cycle assessment (LCA) of a desktop that show that manufacturing and end of life accounts for the majority of this desktop's ecological footprint.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Therefore, the biggest contribution to green computing usually is to prolong the equipment's lifetime.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Another report from Gartner recommends to "Look for product longevity, including upgradability and modularity." For instance, manufacturing a new PC makes a far bigger ecological footprint than manufacturing a new RAM module to upgrade an existing one.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Data center facilities are heavy consumers of energy, accounting for between 1.1% and 1.5% of the world's total energy use in 2010.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Department of Energy estimates that data center facilities consume up to 100 to 200 times more energy than standard office buildings.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Energy efficient data center design should address all of the energy use aspects included in a data center: from the IT equipment to the HVAC (Heating, ventilation and air conditioning) equipment to the actual location, configuration and construction of the building.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Additional energy efficient design opportunities specified by the U.S.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Department of Energy include on-site electrical generation and recycling of waste heat.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Energy efficient data center design should help to better use a data center's space, and increase performance and efficiency.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The efficiency of algorithms affects the amount of computer resources required for any given computing function and there are many efficiency trade-offs in writing programs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Algorithm changes, such as switching from a slow (e.g. linear) search algorithm to a fast (e.g. hashed or indexed) search algorithm can reduce resource usage for a given task from substantial to close to zero.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In 2009, a study by a physicist at Harvard estimated that the average Google search released 7 grams of carbon dioxide (CO2).
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] However, Google disputed this figure, arguing that a typical search produced only 0.2 grams of CO2.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Algorithms can also be used to route data to data centers where electricity is less expensive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Researchers from MIT, Carnegie Mellon University, and Akamai have tested an energy allocation algorithm that routes traffic to the location with the lowest energy costs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The researchers project up to 40 percent savings on energy costs if their proposed algorithm were to be deployed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] However, this approach does not actually reduce the amount of energy being used; it reduces only the cost to the company using it.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Nonetheless, a similar strategy could be used to direct traffic to rely on energy that is produced in a more environmentally friendly or efficient way.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] A similar approach has also been used to cut energy usage by routing traffic away from data centers experiencing warm weather; this allows computers to be shut down to avoid using air conditioning.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Larger server centers are sometimes located where energy and land are inexpensive and readily available.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Local availability of renewable energy, climate that allows outside air to be used for cooling, or locating them where the heat they produce may be used for other purposes could be factors in green siting decisions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Approaches to actually reduce the energy consumption of network devices by proper network/device management techniques have been surveyed Bianzino, et al.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The authors grouped the approaches into 4 main strategies, namely (i) Adaptive Link Rate (ALR), (ii) Interface Proxying, (iii) Energy Aware Infrastructure, and (iv) Maximum Energy Aware Applications.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Computer virtualization refers to the abstraction of computer resources, such as the process of running two or more logical computer systems on one set of physical hardware.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The concept originated with the IBM mainframe operating systems of the 1960s, and was commercialized for x86-compatible computers, and other computer systems, in the 1990s.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] With virtualization, a system administrator can combine several formerly physical systems as virtual machines on one powerful system, thereby conserving resources by removing need for some of the original hardware and reducing power and cooling consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Virtualization can assist in distributing work so that servers are either busy or put in a low-power sleep state.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Several commercial companies and open-source projects now offer software packages to enable a transition to virtual computing.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Intel Corporation and AMD have also built proprietary virtualization enhancements to the x86 instruction set into each of their CPU product lines, in order to facilitate virtual computing.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] New virtual technologies, such as operating system-level virtualization can also be used to reduce energy consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] These technologies make a more efficient use of resources, thus reducing energy consumption by design.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Also, the consolidation of virtualized technologies is more efficient than the one done in virtual machines, so more services can be deployed in the same physical machine, reducing the amount of hardware needed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Terminal servers have also been used in green computing.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] When using the system, users at a terminal connect to a central server; all of the actual computing is done on the server, but the end user experiences the system operating as if it were on the terminal.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] These can be combined with thin clients, which use up to 1/8 the amount of energy of a normal workstation, resulting in a decrease of energy costs and consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] There has been an increase in using terminal services with thin clients to create virtual labs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Examples of terminal server software include Terminal Services for Windows and the Linux Terminal Server Project (LTSP) for the Linux operating system.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Software-based remote desktop clients such as Microsoft Remote Desktop and RealVNC can provide similar thin-client functions when run on low power hardware that connects to a server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Data compression, which involves using fewer bits to encode information, may also be used in green computing depending on the structure of the data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Since it is highly data specific, data compression strategies may result in using more energy or resources than necessary in some cases.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] However, choosing a well-suited compression algorithm for the dataset can yield greater power efficiency and reduce network and storage requirements.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] There is a tradeoff between compression ratio and energy consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Deciding whether or not this is worthwhile depends on the dataset's compressibility.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Compression improves energy efficiency for data with a compression ratio much less than roughly 0.3, and hurts for data with higher compression ratios.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The Advanced Configuration and Power Interface (ACPI), an open industry standard, allows an operating system to directly control the power-saving aspects of its underlying hardware.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This allows a system to automatically turn off components such as monitors and hard drives after set periods of inactivity.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In addition, a system may hibernate, when most components (including the CPU and the system RAM) are turned off.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] ACPI is a successor to an earlier Intel-Microsoft standard called Advanced Power Management, which allows a computer's BIOS to control power management functions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Some programs allow the user to manually adjust the voltages supplied to the CPU, which reduces both the amount of heat produced and electricity consumed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Some CPUs can automatically undervolt the processor, depending on the workload; this technology is called "SpeedStep" on Intel processors, "PowerNow!"/"Cool'n'Quiet" on AMD chips, LongHaul on VIA CPUs, and LongRun with Transmeta processors.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Data centers, which have been criticized for their extraordinarily high energy demand, are a primary focus for proponents of green computing.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] According to a Greenpeace study, data centers represent 21% of the electricity consumed by the IT sector, which is about 382 billion kWh a year.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Data centers can potentially improve their energy and space efficiency through techniques such as storage consolidation and virtualization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Many organizations are aiming to eliminate underused servers, resulting in lower energy usage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The U.S. federal government set a minimum 10% reduction target for data center energy usage by 2011.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] With the aid of a self-styled ultra-efficient evaporative cooling technology.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Google Inc. claims to have reduced its energy consumption to 50% of the industry average.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Cryptocurrency mining, particularly for proof-of-work currencies like Bitcoin, also uses significant amounts of energy globally.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Advocates have argued that cryptocurrency can help to drive investment in green energy.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Microsoft Windows has included limited PC power management features since Windows 95.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] These initially provided for stand-by (suspend-to-RAM) and a monitor low power state.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Further iterations of Windows added hibernate (suspend-to-disk) and support for the ACPI standard.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Windows 2000 was the first NT-based operating system to include power management.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This required major changes to the underlying operating system architecture and a new hardware driver model.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Windows 2000 also introduced Group Policy, a technology that allowed administrators to centrally configure most Windows features.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] However, power management was not one of those features.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This is probably because the power management settings design relied upon a connected set of per-user and per-machine binary registry values, effectively leaving it up to each user to configure their own power management settings.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This approach, which is not compatible with Windows Group Policy, was repeated in Windows XP.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The reasons for this design decision by Microsoft are not known, and it has resulted in heavy criticism.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Microsoft significantly improved this in Windows Vista by redesigning the power management system to allow basic configuration by Group Policy.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The support offered is limited to a single per-computer policy.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Windows 7 retains these limitations but includes refinements for timer coalescing, processor power management, and display panel brightness.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The most significant change in Windows 7 is in the user experience.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The prominence of the default High Performance power plan has been reduced with the aim of encouraging users to save power.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Third-party PC power management software for adds features beyond those built-in to the Windows operating system.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Most products offer Active Directory integration and per-user/per-machine settings with the more advanced offering multiple power plans, scheduled power plans, anti-insomnia features and enterprise power usage reporting.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Linux systems started to provide laptop-optimized power-management in 2005, with power-management options being mainstream since 2009.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Desktop computer power supplies are in general 70–75% efficient, dissipating the remaining energy as heat.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] A certification program called 80 Plus certifies PSUs that are at least 80% efficient; typically these models are drop-in replacements for older, less efficient PSUs of the same form factor.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] As of July 20, 2007, all new Energy Star 4.0-certified desktop PSUs must be at least 80% efficient.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Smaller form factor (e.g., 2.5 inch) hard disk drives often consume less power per gigabyte than physically larger drives.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Unlike hard disk drives, solid-state drives store data in flash memory or DRAM.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] With no moving parts, power consumption may be reduced somewhat for low-capacity flash-based devices.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] As hard drive prices have fallen, storage farms have tended to increase in capacity to make more data available online.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This includes archival and backup data that would formerly have been saved on tape or other offline storage.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The increase in online storage has increased power consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Reducing the power consumed by large storage arrays, while still providing the benefits of online storage, is a subject of ongoing research.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] A fast GPU may be the largest power consumer in a computer.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Unlike other display technologies, electronic paper does not use any power while displaying an image.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] CRT monitors typically use more power than LCD monitors.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] They also contain significant amounts of lead.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] LCD monitors typically use a cold-cathode fluorescent bulb to provide light for the display.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Most newer displays use an array of light-emitting diodes (LEDs) in place of the fluorescent bulb, which further reduces the amount of electricity used by the display.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Fluorescent back-lights also contain mercury, whereas LED back-lights do not.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] A light-on-dark color scheme, also called *dark mode*, is a color scheme that requires less energy to display on new display technologies, such as OLED.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This positively impacts battery life and energy consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] While an OLED will consume around 40% of the power of an LCD displaying an image that is primarily black, it can use more than three times as much power to display an image with a white background, such as a document or web site.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This can lead to reduced battery life and increased energy use, unless a light-on-dark color scheme is used.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] A 2018 article in *Popular Science* suggests that "Dark mode is easier on the eyes and battery" and displaying white on full brightness uses roughly six times as much power as pure black on a Google Pixel, which has an OLED display.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Apple's iOS 13 and iPadOS 13 both feature a light-on dark mode, which would allow third-party developers to implement their own dark themes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Google's Android 10 features a system-level dark mode.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Recycling computing equipment can keep harmful materials such as lead, mercury, and hexavalent chromium out of landfills, and can replace equipment that otherwise would need to be manufactured, saving further energy and emissions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Computer systems that have outlived their original function can be re-purposed, or donated to various charities and non-profit organizations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] However, many charities have recently imposed minimum system requirements for donated equipment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Additionally, parts from outdated systems may be salvaged and recycled through certain retail outlets and municipal or private recycling centers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Computing supplies, such as printer cartridges, paper, and batteries may be recycled as well.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] A drawback to many of these schemes is that computers gathered through recycling drives are often shipped to developing countries where environmental standards are less strict than in North America and Europe.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The Silicon Valley Toxics Coalition has estimated that 80% of the post-consumer e-waste collected for recycling is shipped abroad to countries such as China and India.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In 2011, the collection rate of e-waste remained low, even in the most ecology-responsible countries like France.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In the U.S., e-waste collection was at a 14% annual rate between electronic equipment sold and e-waste collected for 2006 to 2009.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The recycling of old computers raises a privacy issue.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The old storage devices still hold private information, such as emails, passwords, and credit card numbers, which can be recovered simply by using software available freely on the Internet.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Deletion of a file does not actually remove the file from the hard drive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Before recycling a computer, users should remove the hard drive, or hard drives if there is more than one, and physically destroy it or store it somewhere safe.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] There are some authorized hardware recycling companies to whom the computer may be given for recycling, and they typically sign a non-disclosure agreement.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Cloud computing may help to address two major ICT challenges related to green computing – energy usage and embodied carbon.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Hyperscale data centers such as those operated by AWS, Azure, and GCP can benefit from economies of scale, and virtualization, dynamic provisioning environment, multi-tenancy and green data center approaches can enable more efficient resource allocation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Organizations may be able to reduce their direct energy consumption and carbon emissions by up to 30% and 90% respectively by moving certain on-premises applications into the public cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] However, critics point to shortcomings in the carbon tracking and management tools provided by major cloud providers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] GreenOps, also known as DevGreenOps, DevSusOps or DevSustainableOps, is emerging as a framework to include sustainability into cloud management.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Carbon-aware computing and grid-aware computing can form part of a GreenOps approach.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This includes techniques like demand shifting, which means moving computational workloads to locations or times of day with cleaner energy in the grid.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Demand shaping is a similar technique, which focuses on adjusting workloads according to the amount of clean energy currently available.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] New technologies such as edge and fog computing are a solution to reducing energy consumption.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] These technologies allow redistributing computation near its use, thus reducing energy costs in the network.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Furthermore, having smaller data centers, the energy used in operations such as refrigerating and maintenance is reduced.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Remote work using teleconference and telepresence technologies is often implemented in green computing initiatives.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The advantages include increased worker satisfaction, reduction of greenhouse gas emissions related to travel, and increased profit margins as a result of lower overhead costs for office space, heat, lighting, etc.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The average annual energy consumption for U.S. office buildings is over 23 kilowatt hours per square foot, with heat, air conditioning and lighting accounting for 70% of all energy consumed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Other related initiatives, such as Hoteling, reduce the square footage per employee as workers reserve space only when needed.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Many types of jobs, such as sales, consulting, and field service, integrate well with this technique.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Voice over IP (VoIP) reduces the telephony wiring infrastructure by sharing the existing Ethernet copper.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] VoIP and phone extension mobility also made hot desking more practical.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Wi-Fi consume 4 to 10 times less energy than 4G.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In 2013 ICT energy consumption, in the US and worldwide, was estimated respectively at 9.4% and 5.3% of the total electricity produced.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The energy consumption of ICTs is today significant even when compared with other industries.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Some studies have tried to identify the key energy indices that allow a relevant comparison between different devices (network elements).
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] This analysis was focused on how to optimise device and network consumption for carrier telecommunication by itself.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The target was to allow an immediate perception of the relationship between the network technology and the environmental effect.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] These studies are at the start and further research will be necessary.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The Green500 list was first announced on November 15, 2007, at SC|07.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] As a complement to the TOP500, the listing of the Green500 began a new era where supercomputers can be compared by performance-per-watt.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] As of 2019, two Japanese supercomputers topped the Green500 energy efficiency ranking with performance exceeding 16 GFLOPS/watt, and two IBM AC922 systems followed with performance exceeding 15 GFLOPS/watt.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Degree and postgraduate programs provide training in a range of information technology concentrations along with sustainable strategies to educate students on how to build and maintain systems while reducing its harm to the environment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] The Australian National University (ANU) offers "ICT Sustainability" as part of its information technology and engineering masters programs.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Athabasca University offers a similar course "Green ICT Strategies", adapted from the ANU course notes by Tom Worthington.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] In the UK, Leeds Beckett University offers an MSc Sustainable Computing program in both full- and part-time access modes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Since 2010, Greenpeace has maintained a list of ratings of prominent technology companies in several countries based on how clean the energy used by that company is, ranging from A (the best) to F (the worst).
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Digitalization has brought additional energy consumption; energy-increasing effects have been greater than the energy-reducing effects.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Efficiency and rebound effects – Rebound effects are high for ICT and increased productivity often leads to new behaviors that are more energy intensive.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Economic growth – Positive effect of digitalization on economic growth.
[src:hetzner-cloud/green-computing] Sectoral change – Growth of ICT services tends not to replace, but come on top of existing services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner Online GmbH began operations in Germany in 1997 under the name Hetzner Online Services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Between 2000 and 2015, Hetzner Online in Germany operated under the legal status AG ("Aktiengesellschaft").
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In 2015, it changed its legal status to GmbH.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In addition, Hetzner Online expanded its chief executive team with Stephan Konvicka and Günther Müller at the beginning of 2019.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The company is named after its founder Martin Hetzner.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner Online owns and operates three data center parks in Nuremberg and Falkenstein (Germany), and Tuusula (Finland).
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] It also rents colocation space in Ashburn, Virginia (United States), and Hillsboro, Oregon (United States).
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In 2024, Hetzner expanded its global footprint with a new data center in Singapore (Singapore).
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In addition, Hetzner Online is a co-investor in the Cinia C-Lion1 project, which connected Helsinki and Rostock, Germany together with a 1,100 km long submarine fiberglass cable.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The cable provides a high-speed connection between Hetzner's German and Finnish data centers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner Online provides dedicated hosting, shared web hosting, virtual private servers, managed servers, domain names, SSL certificates, storage boxes, and cloud.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] At the data center parks located in Nuremberg, Falkenstein and Tuusula/Finland, customers can also connect their hardware to Hetzner Online's infrastructure and network with the company's colocation services.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The company operates a server auction site online where the chance to rent older dedicated servers (not purchase or colocate) are auctioned off in the form of a Dutch auction.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] According to W3Techs, Hetzner is used by 2.7% of all websites.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner Online has a domain name registrar arrangement with ICANN (for registering domains under .com, .net and .org and others), DENIC (for .de), and nic.at (for .at).
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner Online's datacenter projects are coordinated and implemented in-house with as little outsourcing as possible.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Data center units served by multiple redundant uplinks, including 1300 Gbit/s to DE-CIX and fiber optic links to Nuremberg and Frankfurt.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Colocation facilities are sited at all data center parks in Nuremberg, Falkenstein (Vogtland) in Germany, and Helsinki in Finland.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In 2021, a datacenter in Ashburn, Virginia, was opened, marking Hetzner's first American server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] By 2024, the company took a significant step by opening a datacenter in Singapore, marking Hetzner's first Singaporean server.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In March 2025, Hetzner and MHB Montage launched HT Clean Energy, a solar initiative for data centers, marking a significant move toward reducing the carbon footprint of the company's data center operations.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The backbone is set up in the form of a ring network between the datacenter locations Nuremberg and Falkenstein, as well as the most important Internet location, Frankfurt.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] All locations are connected to central exchange nodes such as DE-CIX, AMS-IX, DATA-IX, and V-IX via the company's own fiber optic network.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] All Hetzner's dedicated servers had a minimum 20 TB monthly cap for full speed on their servers with the option for an extra fee for full speed past that point.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] However, they have lifted the bandwidth cap on 1 Gbit/s connection speeds as of October 1, 2018.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In 2025, Hetzner began upgrading its core network infrastructure using Nokia routing technology.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The upgrade includes the deployment of 7750 SR-1x routers, which support 100G connections and are compatible with higher-capacity interconnects such as 400G and 800G.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In June 2013, Hetzner Online suffered from a security breach where customer information was exposed to attackers who had compromised Hetzner Online's monitoring systems.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] A number of such messages were sent to Ukraine, which was in the midst of undeclared war with Russian paramilitaries in the Donetsk region.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Since the Ukrainian online newspapers did not remove the article, Roskomnadzor sent letters to their internet providers demanding removal of the news item.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner Online complied with the demands and sent a notice to glavcom.ua, saying "Please solve the problem and reply within the next 24 hours to avoid suspension.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] This story was widely reprinted in news sources.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The Ukrainian Ministry of Foreign Affairs issued a statement expressing solidarity with glavcom.ua owners and journalists.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Vassily Zvarych, vice-head of the Communications Department of the Foreign Ministry, gave a press conference saying that he was surprised by Hetzner Online's compliance with the Russian complaint.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The German chapter of Reporters Without Borders also issued a statement condemning Roskomnadzor.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The notices to suspend Glavcom.ua were issued by Hetzner Online August 6, 2014; on August 10 Hetzner Online issued apologies, denying that any censorship was planned and that their technical support made a mistake, which they regretted.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] However, by that time the story was widely published in German mass-media, and Glavcom.ua already migrated from Hetzner Online to another hosting provider.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In 2013, an Estonian anti-spam activist Tõnu Samuel posted a blog entry about an alleged spammer Silver Teede on his website no.spam.ee.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In retaliation, Teede wrote a complaint to the blog's service provider, Hetzner Online, who decided to terminate services for the blog.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In an ensuing court case, Estonian courts found the complaints to be baseless and awarded Samuel damages from Silver Teede for the loss of Samuel's servers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] From April 2015 to December 2015, many of the OS images used by Hetzner's installation program installimage had used duplicate Ed25519 SSH keys.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] This could potentially mean that an attacker could use a man-in-the-middle attack to compromise an SSH connection that was using Ed25519 keys.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner sent an email to all affected customers with any potentially affected servers on information about the issue, and how to fix it.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] On January 11, 2016, Hetzner blocked the St.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Petersburg site of *Novaya Gazeta*, the leading opposition, non-government newspaper in Russia.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The newspaper alleged the act was political censorship without any legal justification.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] On March 7, 2022, during the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, Hetzner disabled the hosting account behind a Ukrainian state-affiliated war information website (war.ukraine.ua).
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Hetzner initially denied blocking the website in question, stating that Cloudflare informed them that the IP does not belong to their network.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Two days later, Hetzner confirmed via a press release that they had erroneously suspended the servers due to "anomalies" found in the account by an employee, which came from a not yet fully developed "plausibility check" and stated that their actions had not been politically motivated.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The press release has since been deleted from the Hetzner website.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In December 2023, Hetzner allegedly sent an email to its users informing them that they will be ending contractual relationship with customers from Russia.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Policy was scheduled to take place on January 31, 2024.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] In November 2025, Hetzner removed the website of the Ukrainian independent media project Zaborona, along with all associated server infrastructure.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] The formal reason given was a two‑month overdue hosting payment amounting to €173.89.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Prior to the shutdown, Hetzner had forwarded several notices from the Russian media regulator Roskomnadzor to Zaborona, requesting the removal of specific articles.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] These included, among others, a report on alleged abuses in areas controlled by Russia.
[src:hetzner-cloud/hetzner] Editor‑in‑chief Kateryna Serhatskova stated that the newsroom had repeatedly informed the provider that Zaborona is a Ukrainian media project and does not fall under Russian jurisdiction.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] It is often used as a measure of computer operating system reliability or stability, in that this time represents the time a computer can be left unattended without crashing or needing to be rebooted for administrative or maintenance purposes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Conversely, long uptime may indicate negligence, because some critical updates can require reboots on some platforms.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] In 2005, Novell reported a server with a 6-year uptime.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] This level of uptime is common when servers are maintained under an industrial context and host critical applications such as banking systems.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Netcraft maintains the uptime records for many thousands of web hosting computers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] A server running Novell NetWare has been reported to have been shut down after 16 years of uptime due to a failing hard disk.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Most Unix-like systems including Linux, FreeBSD, Mac OS X, and SySVr4 have the *uptime* command.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] This command originated in 3.0BSD and has become ubiquitous among Unix systems ever since.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Despite almost always providing the same collection of information and being so ubiquitous, it is not part of any Unix-related standard, neither SUS nor POSIX.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] On Linux, an *uptime* command is part of GNU coreutils, BusyBox and Toybox.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] On BSD, the *uptime* command is hard link to the *w* program.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The *w* program is based on the RSTS/E, TOPS-10, and TOPS-20 SYSTAT program.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Each Unix-like system also has its own private interfaces for obtaining the system uptime.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] On Linux, several procfs files provide information on the system uptime.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The main file is `/proc/uptime`, but `/proc/stat` provides related information too.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The first number is the total number of seconds the system has been up.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The second number is how much of that time the machine has spent idle, in seconds.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] On multi-core systems (and some Linux versions) the second number is the sum of the idle time accumulated by each CPU.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The C API for uptime information is `sysinfo()`.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] On BSD systems and macOS (a combination of BSD and XNU parts), the uptime information is available from the sysctl system, both in the form of the *sysctl* command and the `sysctl()` C function.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] macOS also provides the uptime as `clock_gettime(CLOCK_MONOTONIC_RAW)`, a POSIX interface with implementation-defined starting point; macOS sets the starting point at system boot.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] `mach_timebase_info()` and `CACurrentMediaTime()` are additional ways to access the same raw monotonic clock.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] On FreeBSD (but not macOS), the kernel exports three symbols that can be used as `extern` variables in C to obtain the boot time and uptime.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] They are called `boottime`, `time_second`, and `time_uptime`.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] These require no function call at all to use, unlike `sysctl()`.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Higher-precision uptime is provided from functions such as `microuptime()`.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Some versions of Microsoft Windows include an uptime field in Windows Task Manager, under the "Performance" tab.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The format is D:HH:MM:SS (days, hours, minutes, seconds).
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The output of the `systeminfo` command includes a "System Up Time" or "System Boot Time" field.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The exact text and format are dependent on the language and locale.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The time given by `systeminfo` is not reliable.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] It does not take into account time spent in sleep or hibernation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Thus, the boot time will drift forward every time the computer sleeps or hibernates.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The `NET` command with its `STATISTICS` sub-command provides the date and time the computer started, for both the `NET STATISTICS WORKSTATION` and `NET STATISTICS SERVER` variants.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The command `NET STATS SRV` is shorthand for `NET STATISTICS SERVER`.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The exact text and date format is dependent on the configured language and locale.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Uptime can be determined via Windows Management Instrumentation (WMI), by querying the `LastBootUpTime` property of the `Win32_OperatingSystem` class.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The timestamp uses the format `yyyymmddhhmmss.nnn`, so in the above example, the computer last booted up on 8 May 2011 at 16:17:51.822.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The text "LastBootUpTime" and the timestamp format do not vary with language or locale.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] WMI can also be queried using a variety of application programming interfaces, including VBScript or PowerShell.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] Microsoft formerly provided a downloadable utility called `Uptime.exe`, which reports elapsed time in days, hours, minutes, and seconds.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The time given by `Uptime.exe` is not reliable.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The `uptime` command is also available for FreeDOS.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] On OpenVMS systems, the `show system` command can be used at the DCL command prompt to obtain the system uptime.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The first line of the resulting display includes the system's uptime, displayed as days followed by hours:minutes:seconds.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] In the following example, the command qualifier `/noprocess` suppresses the display of per-process detail lines of information.
[src:hetzner-cloud/uptime] The command output above shows that node JACK on 29 January 2008 at 16:32:04.67 has an uptime of 894 days 22 hours 28 minutes and 52 seconds.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] In computing, **virtualization** (or **virtualisation** in Commonwealth English; see spelling differences,) abbreviated as **v12n**, is a series of technologies that allows dividing of physical computing resources into a series of virtual machines, operating systems, processes or containers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Virtualization began in the 1960s with IBM CP/CMS.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The control program CP provided each user with a simulated stand-alone System/360 computer.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] In hardware virtualization, the *host machine* is the machine that is used by the virtualization and the *guest machine* is the virtual machine.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The words *host* and *guest* are used to distinguish the software that runs on the physical machine from the software that runs on the virtual machine.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The software or firmware that creates a virtual machine on the host hardware is called a *hypervisor* or *virtual machine monitor*.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hardware virtualization is not the same as hardware emulation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Desktop virtualization is the concept of separating the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Operating system-level virtualization, also known as containerization, refers to an operating system feature in which the kernel allows the existence of multiple isolated user-space instances.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The usual goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] A form of virtualization was first demonstrated with IBM's CP-40 research system in 1967, then distributed via open source in CP/CMS in 1967–1972, and re-implemented in IBM's VM family from 1972 to the present.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Each CP/CMS user was provided a simulated, stand-alone computer.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Each such virtual machine had the complete capabilities of the underlying machine, and (for its user) the virtual machine was indistinguishable from a private system.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] This simulation was comprehensive, and was based on the *Principles of Operation* manual for the hardware.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] It thus included such elements as an instruction set, main memory, interrupts, exceptions, and device access.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The result was a single machine that could be multiplexed among many users.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization first appeared on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] IBM added virtual memory hardware to the System/370 series in 1972 which is not the same as Intel VT-x Rings providing a higher privilege level for Hypervisor to properly control Virtual Machines requiring full access to Supervisor and Program or User modes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] With the increasing demand for high-definition computer graphics (e.g.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] CAD), virtualization of mainframes lost some attention in the late 1970s, when the upcoming minicomputers fostered resource allocation through distributed computing, encompassing the commoditization of microcomputers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The increase in compute capacity per x86 server (and in particular the substantial increase in modern networks' bandwidths) rekindled interest in data-center based computing which is based on virtualization techniques.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The primary driver was the potential for server consolidation: virtualization allowed a single server to cost-efficiently consolidate compute power on multiple underutilized dedicated servers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The most visible hallmark of a return to the roots of computing is cloud computing, which is a synonym for data center based computing (or mainframe-like computing) through high bandwidth networks.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] It is closely connected to virtualization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] This made it difficult to implement a virtual machine monitor for this type of processor.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Specific limitations included the inability to trap on some privileged instructions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Therefore, to compensate for these architectural limitations, designers accomplished virtualization of the x86 architecture through two methods: **full virtualization** or **paravirtualization**.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Both create the illusion of physical hardware to achieve the goal of operating system independence from the hardware but present some trade-offs in performance and complexity.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Full virtualization was not fully available on the x86 platform prior to 2005.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Many platform hypervisors for the x86 platform came very close and claimed full virtualization (such as Adeos, Mac-on-Linux, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Parallels Workstation, VMware Workstation, VMware Server (formerly GSX Server), VirtualBox, Win4BSD, and Win4Lin Pro).
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD (working independently) created new processor extensions to the x86 architecture called Intel VT-x and AMD-V, respectively.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] On the Itanium architecture, hardware-assisted virtualization is known as VT-i.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Software executed on these virtual machines is separated from the underlying hardware resources.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] For example, a computer that is running Arch Linux may host a virtual machine that looks like a computer with the Microsoft Windows operating system; Windows-based software can be run on the virtual machine.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Full virtualization employs techniques that pools physical computer resources into one or more instances; each running a virtual environment where any software or operating system capable of execution on the raw hardware can be run in the virtual machine.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Two common full virtualization techniques are typically used: (a) binary translation and (b) hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Binary translation automatically modifies the software on-the-fly to replace instructions that "pierce the virtual machine" with a different, virtual machine safe sequence of instructions.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization allows guest operating systems to be run in isolation with virtually no modification to the (guest) operating system.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Some hypervisors perform binary translation between guest and host, either between differing instruction set architectures or between a guest and host using the same instruction set.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The hypervisor may be designed to interpret a guest's machine code directly or generate machine code for the host's architecture in a form of dynamic binary translation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Most common hypervisors, including ones that use hardware to assist virtualization, perform binary translation of some instructions relating to hardware access.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] In such a case, the hypervisor will trap the instruction and perform the functions to emulate the required devices.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hypervisors that perform binary translation may also be designed to substitute instructions within the guest context to aid security or performance.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization (or *accelerated virtualization; Xen calls it hardware virtual machine (HVM), and Virtual Iron calls it native virtualization)* is a way of improving overall efficiency of hardware virtualization using help from the host processors.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] A full virtualization is used to emulate a complete hardware environment, or virtual machine, in which an unmodified guest operating system (using the same instruction set as the host machine) effectively executes in complete isolation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM 308X processors in 1980, with the Start Interpretive Execution (SIE) instruction.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] It was added to x86 processors (Intel VT-x, AMD-V or VIA VT) in 2005, 2006 and 2010 respectively.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] IBM offers hardware virtualization for its IBM Power Systems hardware for AIX, Linux and IBM i, and for its IBM Z mainframes.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] IBM refers to its specific form of hardware virtualization as "logical partition", or more commonly as LPAR.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization reduces the maintenance overhead of binary translation based virtualization as it reduces (ideally, eliminates) the code that needs to be translated in the guest operating system.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] It is also considerably easier to obtain better performance.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Paravirtualization is a virtualization technique that presents a software interface to the virtual machines which is similar, yet not identical, to the underlying hardware–software interface.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Paravirtualization improves performance and efficiency, compared to full virtualization, by having the guest operating system communicate with the hypervisor.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] By allowing the guest operating system to indicate its intent to the hypervisor, each can cooperate to obtain better performance when running in a virtual machine.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The intent of the modified interface is to reduce the portion of the guest's execution time spent performing operations which are substantially more difficult to run in a virtual environment compared to a non-virtualized environment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The paravirtualization provides specially defined 'hooks' to allow the guest(s) and host to request and acknowledge these tasks, which would otherwise be executed in the virtual domain (where execution performance is worse).
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] A successful paravirtualized platform may allow the virtual machine monitor (VMM) to be simpler (by relocating execution of critical tasks from the virtual domain to the host domain), and/or reduce the overall performance degradation of machine execution inside the virtual guest.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Paravirtualization requires the guest operating system to be explicitly ported for the para-API – a conventional OS distribution that is not paravirtualization-aware can still run on a paravirtualizing VMM.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] However, even in cases where the operating system cannot be modified, components may be available that enable many of the significant performance advantages of paravirtualization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] For example, the Xen Windows GPLPV project provides a kit of paravirtualization-aware device drivers, that are intended to be installed into a Microsoft Windows virtual guest running on the Xen hypervisor.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Such applications tend to be accessible through the paravirtual machine interface environment.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] This ensures run-mode compatibility across multiple encryption algorithm models, allowing seamless integration within the paravirtual framework.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The term "paravirtualization" was first used in the research literature in association with the Denali Virtual Machine Manager.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The term is also used to describe the Xen, L4, TRANGO, VMware, Wind River and XtratuM hypervisors.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] All these projects use or can use paravirtualization techniques to support high performance virtual machines on x86 hardware by implementing a virtual machine that does not implement the hard-to-virtualize parts of the actual x86 instruction set.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] In 2005, VMware proposed a paravirtualization interface, the Virtual Machine Interface (VMI), as a communication mechanism between the guest operating system and the hypervisor.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] This interface enabled transparent paravirtualization in which a single binary version of the operating system can run either on native hardware or on a hypervisor in paravirtualized mode.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The first appearance of paravirtualization support in Linux occurred with the merge of the ppc64 port in 2002, which supported running Linux as a paravirtualized guest on IBM pSeries (RS/6000) and iSeries (AS/400) hardware.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] At the USENIX conference in 2006 in Boston, Massachusetts, a number of Linux development vendors (including IBM, VMware, Xen, and Red Hat) collaborated on an alternative form of paravirtualization, initially developed by the Xen group, called "paravirt-ops".
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The paravirt-ops code (often shortened to pv-ops) was included in the mainline Linux kernel as of the 2.6.23 version, and provides a hypervisor-agnostic interface between the hypervisor and guest kernels.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Distribution support for pv-ops guest kernels appeared starting with Ubuntu 7.04 and RedHat 9.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Xen hypervisors based on any 2.6.24 or later kernel support pv-ops guests, as does VMware's Workstation product beginning with version 6.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Hybrid virtualization combines full virtualization techniques with paravirtualized drivers to overcome limitations with hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] A hardware-assisted full virtualization approach uses an unmodified guest operating system that involves many VM traps producing high CPU overheads limiting scalability and the efficiency of server consolidation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] The hybrid virtualization approach overcomes this problem.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Desktop virtualization separates the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] One form of desktop virtualization, virtual desktop infrastructure (VDI), can be thought of as a more advanced form of hardware virtualization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Rather than interacting with a host computer directly via a keyboard, mouse, and monitor, the user interacts with the host computer using another desktop computer or a mobile device by means of a network connection, such as a LAN, Wireless LAN or even the Internet.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] In addition, the host computer in this scenario becomes a server computer capable of hosting multiple virtual machines at the same time for multiple users.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Companies like HP and IBM provide a hybrid VDI model with a range of virtualization software and delivery models to improve upon the limitations of distributed client computing.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Selected client environments move workloads from PCs and other devices to data center servers, creating well-managed virtual clients, with applications and client operating environments hosted on servers and storage in the data center.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] For users, this means they can access their desktop from any location, without being tied to a single client device.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Since the resources are centralized, users moving between work locations can still access the same client environment with their applications and data.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] For IT administrators, this means a more centralized, efficient client environment that is easier to maintain and able to more quickly respond to the changing needs of the user and business.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Another form, session virtualization, allows multiple users to connect and log into a shared but powerful computer over the network and use it simultaneously.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Each is given a desktop and a personal folder in which they store their files.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] With multiseat configuration, session virtualization can be accomplished using a single PC with multiple monitors, keyboards, and mice connected.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Thin clients, which are seen in desktop virtualization, are simple and/or cheap computers that are primarily designed to connect to the network.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] They may lack significant hard disk storage space, RAM or even processing power, but many organizations are beginning to look at the cost benefits of eliminating "thick client" desktops that are packed with software (and require software licensing fees) and making more strategic investments.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Desktop virtualization simplifies software versioning and patch management, where the new image is simply updated on the server, and the desktop gets the updated version when it reboots.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] It also enables centralized control over what applications the user is allowed to have access to on the workstation.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Moving virtualized desktops into the cloud creates hosted virtual desktops (HVDs), in which the desktop images are centrally managed and maintained by a specialist hosting firm.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Benefits include scalability and the reduction of capital expenditure, which is replaced by a monthly operational cost.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Such instances, called containers, partitions, virtual environments (VEs) or jails (FreeBSD jail or chroot jail), may look like (physical) computers from the point of view of programs running in them.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] A computer program running on an ordinary operating system can see all resources (connected devices, files and folders, network shares, CPU power, quantifiable hardware capabilities) of that computer.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] However, programs running inside a container can only see the container's contents and devices assigned to the container.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] This provides many of the benefits that virtual machines have such as standardization and scalability, while using less resources as the kernel is shared between containers.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Containerization started gaining prominence in 2014, with the introduction of Docker.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] A common goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] With virtualization, several operating systems can be run in parallel on a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] This parallelism tends to reduce overhead costs and differs from multitasking, which involves running several programs on the same OS.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Using virtualization, an enterprise can better manage updates and rapid changes to the operating system and applications without disrupting the user.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Ultimately, virtualization dramatically improves the efficiency and availability of resources and applications in an organization.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Instead of relying on the old model of "one server, one application" that leads to underutilized resources, virtual resources are dynamically applied to meet business needs without any excess fat".
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] Virtual machines running proprietary operating systems require licensing, regardless of the host machine's operating system.
[src:hetzner-cloud/virtualization] For example, installing Microsoft Windows into a VM guest requires its licensing requirements to be satisfied.
